{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e7e94f96-8c9f-4b70-811a-695f72f17106","content":"CLR activation logs are **not the right tool** for diagnosing a `NullReferenceException`. Here's why:\n\n- **CLR activation logs** diagnose runtime *loading* issues (wrong runtime version picked, runtime fails to load, .NET 3.5 FOD dialogs, etc.)\n- **NullReferenceException** is an application-level bug — your code is dereferencing a null reference after the runtime has already loaded successfully.\n\n**To diagnose your NullReferenceException, you'd want:**\n\n1. **The stack trace** from the exception (shows exactly which line is null)\n2. **A crash dump** (analyzable with `dotnet-dump` or WinDbg)\n3. **Application logs** around startup\n\nCould you share the exception stack trace or a crash dump? That will pinpoint the null reference far more effectively than CLR activation logs.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"41f2f842-4cd3-4108-b643-89632d8fe464","outputTokens":203,"requestId":"C3C1:A78B9:1EFE1B7:22E1FAB:6A07CB1F"},"id":"79419e4b-85a9-4c66-be3d-e8017ccacb12","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:40:53.243Z","parentId":"c60f9292-306b-4983-93e6-58e8ff9edc2b"}
